@DiabeticCrab, I suspect that you're hitting a Mesa bug (or, just possibly, a kernel bug) which is causing as it's causing a (partial) desktop crash. If so then the kernel log and possibly xorg.log (and the Wayland equivalent) would be more useful (though I note that you referred to the kernel log showing nothing obvious).

It's worth trying older kernels and/or older versions of Mesa. Also worth testing without Wayland.

(Quickly tested here without problem other than the usual refusal to start in multi-player mode. Devuan stable, Xfce4 desktop, RX 6600 XT, Mesa 23.3.3, Linux 6.5.13; Proton 8.0-5.)

@mbriar 
Don't know what the exact `32bit nvidia driver` of archlinux is, `lib32-nvidia-utils`? 

BTW: I'm using `nvidia-open` as the Nvidia GPU driver if it matters.

@jamincollins, I forgot a detail that's critical to your system.

You have a Renoir GPU. Renoir has GFX9 inside of it (https://www.x.org/wiki/RadeonFeature/#radeongraphicscomputehardware), and AMDVLK has dropped support for GFX9 in v-2023.Q4.1 (`Drop support for gfx8-9 ASICs` at https://github.com/GPUOpen-Drivers/AMDVLK/releases/tag/v-2023.Q4.1).

Future versions of AMDVLK will also not support your GPU, so there's nothing for an Arch package maintainer to fix. Reconfigure your system to use RADV.

